description: Welcome to the world of tomorrow, where anyone could be a Trigger...even you. In the not too distant future, 87% of America's corporations have been consolidated into one government-sanctioned corporate entity: Ethicorp. The result has allowed our country's citizens to live safely and securely in a clean, terror-free, and productive environment. Society is dosed on nonstop Vid feeds, feel-good drugs, clean sex and low crime. And most people happily embrace Ethicorp's corporate motto: "We Get the Bad Out!" This is the world of TRIGGER, an all-new ongoing futuristic thriller written by Jason Hall (BEWARE THE CREEPER) with dazzling art by John Watkiss (SANDMAN MYSTERY THEATRE) that captures the look and feel of Blade Runner, Minority Report and Sky Captain and the World of Tomorrow! To keep society so "shiny," Ethicorp secretly controls legions of high-tech killers, known on the street as "Triggers", that act as one-man (or woman) judge, jury and executioner whenever Ethicorp sees something "bad." But be careful, because "bad," like beauty, is often in the eye of the beholder. Don't miss this thrilling new series, brought to you by the fine folks at Ethicorp and VERTIGO.
name: Trigger

description:
Volume 3

Follows Manhunter (1988) and Manhunter (1994).

The series has been collected in trades:

  • #1-5: Street Justice
  • #6-14: Trial by Fire
  • #15-23: Origins
  • #24-30: Unleashed
  • #31-38: Forgotten

Federal Prosecutor Kate Spencer was the latest hero to use the Manhunter name, as writer Marc Andreyko and penciller Jesus Saiz gave the world a very different take on the hero, with only minor links to those who had gone before.

Kate, a prosecutor, became a ruthless vigilante after watching yet another super powered criminal escape justice - the mutated cannibal known as Copperhead. After Copperhead avoided the death penalty and escaped from police custody, Spencer stole impounded equipment (including a Darkstar powersuit and a staff that chiefly came from 1980s Manhunter Mark Shaw) to help her track down and kill Copperhead. As a chain-smoking mother who put her job before her child, and with a dramatic costume that covered her whole body, this Manhunter was a fresh take on super heroes and gained a loyal following throughout its 38 issue run.
name: Manhunter

description:
Kat Farrell hates "capes" (superheroes). Unfortunately for her, that's her beat as a Daily Bugle reporter. As a mysterious new vigilante appears, leaving in his wake a body count of super-villains, it is left to Kat to solve the mystery of the Judge. Kat Farrell is introduced in this four-issue limited series, showing her interactions with the Marvel Universe's heroes and villains in order to stop the enigmatic Judge from killing again. Notable appearances by the Tinkerer, the New York franchise of the Bar With No Name, and the almost completely insignificant death the lesser-known Carjack, this series reveals the final disposition of the Tinkerer's son, Rick Mason, the Agent.

With art by Guy Davis (Sandman Mystery Theatre, B.P.R.D.) and written by Bill Rosemann, this story was reprinted in a softcover trade paperback.
name: Deadline

description:
The Wacky Races series was based on the Hannah- Barbera cartoon, about 11 racing cars and their occupants. Each driver was competing to become known as the "World's Wackiest Racer"! The featured characters and their cars were numbered as follows: 
Car 00 - Dick Dastardly and Muttley in the Mean Machine - these two were really the stars of the show / comic as the emphasis was often placed on the lengths these two would go to in order to sabotage the chances of other racers. 
 Car 01 The Slag brothers in the Bouldermobile. A couple of cavemen who would hit others & each other with their clubs. 
Car 02 The Gruesome Twosome in the Creepy Coupe. A dodgy looking couple looking as if they were based on Frankenstein's monster 
Car 03 Professor Pat Pending in the converter-car. An eccentric inventor who could adapt his vehicle to its circumstances 
Car 04 Red Max in the Crimson Haybailer. A pilot and vehicle from WWII 
Car 05 Penelope Pitstop in the Compact Pussycat. The eye candy of the races. Penny just had to flutter her eyelashes if she were ever in trouble and Peter Perfect (see car 09 below) would rush to the rescue, even if it meant him losing the race as a result. 
Car 06 Sergeant Blast and Private Meekly in the Army Surplus Special. Two members of the U.S. military in a souped-up tank. 
Car 07 The Ant Hill Mob in the bulletproof bomb. A 1930's group of mobsters - based on the likes of James Cagney - in a stylish vehicle from the same time period. 
Car 08 Lazy Luke and Blubber Bear in the Arkansas Chugabug. Easy going pair in a ramshackle vehicle that just kept chugging along (and I mean Just!) 
Car09 Peter Perfect in The Turbo Terrific. Suave type of character - perfect gent - always keen to impress Penelope Pitstop (car 05) 
car10 Rufus Ruffcut and Sawtooth in the Buzzwagon. A lumberjack and his pet Beaver in a car made of logs. 
The 7 issues of the volume feature the above characters in a variety of tracks and conditions as they race to the finish line.
name: Wacky Races

description:
The energies of the DC Universe were being altered. In Genesis, a four issue cosmic crossover event written by John Byrne and drawn by Ron Wagner, with covers by Alan Davis, the Flash was losing his speed, Green Lantern's ring was malfunctioning, and Captain Marvel had lost his magic. All over the earth, Super heroes' powers were going haywire, and only the gods knew what was going on. The planet's heroes gathered to ponder their current situation, but found their world attacked by a panicking alien armada. Then, just as the violence was about to escalate, Highfather of the New Gods appeared before the assembled forces and explained the situation.

The Godwave, the force that created all known life in the universe, had passed twice across the universe - creating gods and planets on its first pass, and superhumans on its second - an dit was now contracting. A natural force of power, the Godwave was preparing to explode outward and erase all life in the universe. The only way to stop the grand extinction was to send a small party of heroes inside the mystical source itself to combat the threat. As the citizens of Earth rioted and despaired, a band of heroes led by New God Takion journeyed beyond the walls of teh Source and helped remake the entire cosmos.
name: Genesis

description:
Collected in Desolation Jones (#1-6).

Writer Warren Ellis added a new bizarre hero to his repertoire with Desolation Jones. Michael Jones was an agent of MI6 when he took part in the Desolation Test. The test changed him physically and mentally, turning his hair white and giving him a very personal view of reality. His first story arc involved a conspiracy theory and the legacy of the Third Reich in a superbly twisted cyberpunk - style tale illustrated by J.H. Williams III.
name: Desolation Jones
